            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco De Souza is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog and its ever-shifting cultural tides. Born to a Brazilian immigrant father who brought the warmth of S\u00e3o Paulo to their small Richmond District apartment, and a third-generation Irish-American mother from the Sunset, Marco\u2019s upbringing was a blend of vibrant stories and quiet, working-class resilience. He navigated the city not as a glittering prize, but as a sprawling, familiar backyard.\n\nForegoing a traditional four-year university, Marco, ever the pragmatist, earned an Associate's degree in Business Administration from City College of San Francisco. He valued hustle over pedigree, a lesson learned from watching his parents work multiple jobs. His entry into real estate wasn't a grand ambition but a savvy pivot. Working as an administrative assistant during the dot-com bust of the early 2000s, he saw carnage but also opportunity in the empty office spaces. He got his license and dedicated himself to the unglamorous but vital world of commercial brokerage, learning to read the city not through its skyline, but through its long-term lease agreements.\n\nThe key turning point in his personal life was his divorce five years ago. The amicable split from his college sweetheart left him with a handsome Marina condo, a meticulously maintained Audi, and a quiet sense of solitude. The experience solidified his focus on his career, where deals provided a clarity that relationships often lacked. He now navigates a complex internal conflict: he cherishes the memory of the affordable, eclectic city of his youth while simultaneously profiting from the tech-fueled economy that is displacing it.\n\nHis days are structured: a 6 a.m. workout at a private gym, a short drive to his Financial District office, and evenings often spent entertaining clients or enjoying a quiet dinner alone. At 45, Marco\u2019s ambition has shifted from climbing the corporate ladder to achieving independence. His dream is to open his own boutique brokerage firm, a small but respected name in the industry. He hopes, too, for a lasting partnership, someone who understands both the ambitious man he is and the nostalgic boy from the Richmond District he\u2019ll always be."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the smell of his father\u2019s feijoada simmering on a foggy Sunday afternoon. He was eight, sitting at the kitchen table in their small Richmond apartment, the steam from the pot mingling with the endless gray outside the window. The rich, savory aroma was a shield against the city\u2019s chill. It wasn\u2019t just food; it was warmth, security, and the feeling of a vibrant world contained within their four walls. That memory became his definition of home: a hard-earned comfort that profits and property could never truly replicate.\n\n2.\nAt twenty-two, during the dot-com bust, he walked through a bankrupt startup\u2019s office. His task was to inventory assets for liquidation. Amid the Aeron chairs and forlorn ping-pong tables, he saw a whiteboard covered in faded dreams and stock projections. He felt no pity, only a cold, thrilling clarity. He wasn't looking at a failed company; he was looking at 10,000 square feet of prime real estate, leased and abandoned. In that moment, the abstract idea of \u201chustle\u201d became a tangible strategy, shaping his pragmatic, unsentimental approach to business.\n\n3.\nThe divorce was finalized not in a courtroom, but over the granite countertop of the Marina condo he was keeping. He and his ex-wife signed the last document in silence, then slid the pens back into the holder. There was no shouting, just a profound, shared exhaustion. When she left, the click of the lock echoed in the sudden emptiness. That silence became his companion, solidifying his reliance on the clean, predictable logic of a deal over the messy complexities of the heart. This happened five years ago, at age forty.\n\n4.\nThree years ago, he closed the biggest deal of his career, leasing three full floors in SoMa to a colossal tech firm. The commission was staggering. At the celebratory dinner, looking out from the sleek high-rise restaurant, he pointed out the building to his client. He didn't mention that the new tower stood on the grave of a block he and his friends used to frequent for its cheap diners and dive bars. That night, the pride in his success was tinged with the metallic taste of complicity, cementing his internal conflict.\n\n5.\nJust last month, driving his Audi home late from a client dinner, he stopped at the crest of a hill with a clear view of the Financial District. The towers he\u2019d helped fill glittered below. For a moment, he felt a supreme sense of mastery over the city. Then, an acute awareness of the empty passenger seat beside him hit with surprising force. The ambition to build his own firm crystallized then, not just for independence, but from a deep yearning to have someone to share the view with."
